Abstract¶

When people are buying or selling a house, the biggest thing they care about is the sales price. Buyers usually have their dream house checklist including: number of bedrooms/bathrooms, house age, kitchen finishes, and the quality of the schools and surronding neighborhood. Sellers want to know what factors impact the sales price the most. An example of this is whether doing a last minute remodel or staging the house correctly can increase the value of their housel

I got my dataset from Kaggle, it has 79 explanatory variables describing (almost) every aspect of residential homes in Ames, Iowa. The goal of this project is to build a model to predict the final house sale price of each home using Python. Additionally I wanted try to find out the features that have the biggest influcene on the final price.

Overview¶

This project is using Python langugage. The package I'm using are pandas, numpy,matplotlib, seaborn, sklearn scipy.stats etc. These package are very powerful when doing anaysis and building models.

There are 1460 instances of training data and 1460 of test data. Total number of attributes equals 81, of which 36 is quantitative, 43 categorical + Id and SalePrice.

Quantitative: 1stFlrSF, 2ndFlrSF, 3SsnPorch, BedroomAbvGr, BsmtFinSF1, BsmtFinSF2, BsmtFullBath, BsmtHalfBath, BsmtUnfSF, EnclosedPorch, Fireplaces, FullBath, GarageArea, GarageCars, GarageYrBlt, GrLivArea, HalfBath, KitchenAbvGr, LotArea, LotFrontage, LowQualFinSF, MSSubClass, MasVnrArea, MiscVal, MoSold, OpenPorchSF, OverallCond, OverallQual, PoolArea, ScreenPorch, TotRmsAbvGrd, TotalBsmtSF, WoodDeckSF, YearBuilt, YearRemodAdd, YrSold

Qualitative: Alley, BldgType, BsmtCond, BsmtExposure, BsmtFinType1, BsmtFinType2, BsmtQual, CentralAir, Condition1, Condition2, Electrical, ExterCond, ExterQual, Exterior1st, Exterior2nd, Fence, FireplaceQu, Foundation, Functional, GarageCond, GarageFinish, GarageQual, GarageType, Heating, HeatingQC, HouseStyle, KitchenQual, LandContour, LandSlope, LotConfig, LotShape, MSZoning, MasVnrType, MiscFeature, Neighborhood, PavedDrive, PoolQC, RoofMatl, RoofStyle, SaleCondition, SaleType, Street, Utilities.

Our target variable is SalePrice. It is numerical, so regression algorithms are proper candidates.

The Overall project will including data cleaning, data preprocessing, building and validating models.

Target variable: Sales Price Analysis¶

First thing first, let take a look of the target variable, SalePrice. The SalePrice is skewed, the skewness is 1.88, and kurtosis is 6.5. it is not normalized. Log transformation is a proper one. after log transformed, it is much mormalized, the skewness is 0.12 and kurtosis is 0.81.

Data Cleaning¶

Now that we have some insights about data, we need to preprocess them for the modeling part. The main steps are:

  • Looking at potential NaN
  • remove outlier
  • remove unnecessary features
  • data transformation
  • Normalization
  • Dealing with categorical features (e.g. Dummy coding)

Usually, in a real-world project, the test data are not available until the end. For this reason, test data should contain the same type of data of the training set to preprocess them in the same way. Here, the test set is available. It contains some observations not present in the training dataset and,the use of dummy coding could raise several issues (I spent a lot of time figuring out why I was not able to make predictions on the test set). The easiest way to solve this problem (that is not applicable if test data are not available) is to concatenate Train and Test sets, preprocess, and divide them again.

First Id need to be removed, it is unique value for each record, don't contribute any extra infomation for our model.

Dealing with NA data¶

First check the missing data. And based on the data discription to fill in the missing records. There are few strategies I'm going to use:

  • based on the defination, some features with no values means they don't have the feature, such as garage, fireplace etc, fill the missing value with None.
  • fill the missing value with the appears most often value
  • for numeric features, fill n/a with mean

Remove Unuseful Features¶

When a feature that more than 90% data have same value, then the feature is useless. it does not bring too much information to the model. I will just remove them.

data transformation¶

Now it's time to do some data engeering. I will do following steps:

  • generate a new feature Porch by adding all porch related data
  • add new feature Remodel if the house has remodeled
  • generate a new feature TotBathroom by add FullBath and halfBath togeter
  • assign ordered number to all ordinal features, if the house doesn't have the featues, assign 0 to it.
  • coverate data type
  • remove all useless features
In [16]:
def data_transformation(df):
    data = df.copy()
    data["Porch"] = data["OpenPorchSF"]+data["EnclosedPorch"] + data["3SsnPorch"] + data["ScreenPorch"] 
    #data["CentralAir"]= data["CentralAir"].map({"Y":1, "N":0})
    #data["Electrical"] = data["Electrical"].apply(lambda x: 1 if x=="SBrkr" else 0)
    #data["Pool"] = data["PoolQC"].apply(lambda x: 0 if x=="None" else 1)
    data["TotBathroom"] = data["FullBath"] + 0.5* data["HalfBath"] 
    data["Remodel"] = (data["YearRemodAdd"] - data["YearBuilt"]).apply(lambda x: 1 if x>1 else 0)
 
    colnames = ["BsmtFinSF1","BsmtFinSF2","BsmtUnfSF", #TotalBsmtSF = BsmtFinSF1+BsmtFinSF1 + BsmtUnfSF
                "OpenPorchSF","EnclosedPorch","3SsnPorch","ScreenPorch", 
                "1stFlrSF","2ndFlrSF", #GrLivArea = 1stFlrSF + 2ndFlrSF
                "FullBath", "HalfBath", "YearRemodAdd",
                "GarageYrBlt", "BsmtFinType2"]
    delete_col= list(set(colnames) | set(del_var))
    
    data = data.drop(delete_col, axis=1, inplace=False)
    return data

deal with ordinal features¶

There are lots of features are ordinal feature, we can label them as ordered numbers. for example, all Quality and Condition features, GarageFinish, BsmtFinType. etc. I'm going to label them as 0 if they don't have the feature, 1 if pool, 2 if Fair and so on.

In [17]:
def ordinal_feature_transformation(df):
    data = df.copy()
    categorical_ordinal_feature = ["ExterQual","ExterCond","BsmtQual","BsmtCond","HeatingQC",
                                   "KitchenQual","FireplaceQu","GarageQual"]
    
    for i in categorical_ordinal_feature:
        data[i] = data[i].map({"None":0, "Po":1, "Fa":2, "TA":3, "Gd":4, "Ex":5})
    
    data['LotShape']= data["LotShape"].map({"Reg":4, "IR1":3, "IR2":2, "IR3":1})
    data['LandContour'] = data['LandContour'].map({"Lvl":4, "Bnk":3, "Low":2, "HLS":1})
    data["BsmtExposure"] = data["BsmtExposure"].map({"None":0, "No":1, "Mn":2, "Av":3, "Gd":4}) 
    data["BsmtFinType1"] = data["BsmtFinType1"].map({"None":0, "Unf":1, "LwQ":2, "Rec":3, "BLQ":4, "ALQ":5, "GLQ":6})
    #df["BsmtFinType2"] = df["BsmtFinType2"].map({"NA":0, "Unf":1, "LwQ":2, "Rec":3, "BLQ":4, "ALQ":5, "GLQ":6})
    data["GarageFinish"] = data["GarageFinish"].map({"None":0, "Unf":1, "RFn":2, "Fin":3})
    
    return data

feature type converting¶

Based on the data defination, MSSubClass should be categorical data. We have two column YrSold and MoSold, I'm tying not to deal with time series, I will convert it to factor as well.

In [18]:
# Converting non-numeric predictors stored as numbers into string

def type_convert(df):
    data = df.copy() 
    data['MSSubClass'] = data['MSSubClass'].astype(object)
    data['YrSold'] = data['YrSold'].astype(object)
    data['MoSold'] = data['MoSold'].astype(object)
    data["LotArea"] = data["LotArea"].astype(float)
    data["BsmtFinType1"] = data["BsmtFinType1"].astype(int)
    data["GrLivArea"] = data["GrLivArea"].astype(float)
    data["WoodDeckSF"] = data["WoodDeckSF"].astype(float)
    data["BsmtFullBath"] = data["BsmtFullBath"].astype(int)
    data["GarageCars"] = data["GarageCars"]. astype(int)
    data["Porch"] = data["Porch"].astype(float)
    data["YearBuilt"] = data["YearBuilt"].astype(int)
    return data

def numerical_feature_transfer(df):
    data = df.copy()
    data["LotFrontage"] = st.boxcox(data["LotFrontage"])[0] 
    data["LotArea"] =  st.boxcox(data["LotArea"])[0]
    data["MasVnrArea"] = data["MasVnrArea"] **0.25
    data["TotalBsmtSF"] = np.log1p(data["TotalBsmtSF"])
    data["GrLivArea"] = np.log1p(data["GrLivArea"])
    data["WoodDeckSF"] = data["WoodDeckSF"]**0.5
    data["Porch"] = np.log1p(data["Porch"])
    
    return data

Multicollinearity features¶

Multicollinearity can cause problem when building regression method as all variables should be independent, and it will also cause undermines the statistical significance of an independent variable. Before we do any furthur treatment. let's take a look of current heatmap. Below heatmap shows the correlation between all numerical features.

In [27]:
def high_multicollinear_features(df, threshold =0.7):
    high_corr_data = df[most_corr_features]
    high_corr_data = high_corr_data.loc[:,high_corr_data.columns != "SalePrice"]
    r = high_corr_data.corr()
    idx = np.abs(np.tril(r, k= -1)) < threshold
    idx_keep = np.all(idx, axis=1)
    data_uncorr = high_corr_data.iloc[:,idx_keep]
    dropped_columns=high_corr_data.columns.difference(high_corr_data.columns[idx_keep])
    #plt.figure(figsize=(12,10))
    #sns.heatmap(data_uncorr.corr(), annot= True, fmt=".2f", cmap="coolwarm")
    mask = np.zeros_like(data_uncorr.corr())
    mask[np.triu_indices_from(mask)]=True
    cmap = sns.diverging_palette(180, 30, as_cmap=True)
    with sns.axes_style('white'):
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(25,25))
        sns.heatmap(data_uncorr.corr(),  mask=mask, cmap=cmap, annot=True, center=0, vmin=-1, vmax=0.8,
                square=True, cbar_kws={'shrink':.5, 'orientation': 'vertical'}, linewidth=.02);
    return dropped_columns

# categorical features transformation
def categorical_feature_transformation(df):
    data = df.copy()
    data["LotConfig"] = data["LotConfig"].apply(lambda x: "FR" if (x =="FR2" or x =="FR3") else x)
    data["Condition1"] = data["Condition1"].map({"Artery":"Artery","Feedr":"Feedr","Norm":"Norm","RRNn":"RR", "RRAn":"RR", 
                                             "RRNe":"RR","RRAe":"RR", "PosN":"Pos", "PosA":"Pos"})
    data["RoofStyle"] = data["RoofStyle"].apply(lambda x: "Other" if (x =="Gambrel" or x =="Mansard" 
                                                                  or x=="Shed" or x =="Flat") else x)
   # data["GarageType"] = data["GarageType"].apply(lambda x: "None" if x =="CarPort" else ("Attchd" if x=="2Types" else x))
    data["GarageType"] = data["GarageType"].map({"Attchd":"Attchd", "BuiltIn":"Attchd", 
                                                 "Basement":"Attchd","2Types":"Attchd",
                                                "Carport":"None", "None":"None", 
                                                "Detchd":"Detchd" })
  
    data["SaleType"] = data["SaleType"].map({"WD":"WD","CWD":"WD","VWD":"WD",
                                         "New":"New", 
                                         "COD":"COD",
                                         "Con":"Con","ConLw":"Con","ConLI":"Con","ConLD":"Con",
                                        "Oth":"Other"})
    data = data.drop(["MoSold","YrSold"], axis = 1, inplace= False)
    return data

Modelling¶

Sale price is continue numerical features, so regression is the proper method for this kind of data. I will try different regression algorithms:

  • Linear Regression
  • Ridge Regression
  • Lasso Regression
  • Elastic Net Regression
  • Support Vector Regression Regression
  • Decision Tree Regression
  • Random Forest Regression
  • XGBoost Regression

For each algorithms, I will perform parameter tuning, using RMSE to choose the best score parameter, then compare them together. Five folds cross validation will be performed.

split the train and test data¶

create RMSE(root-mean-square error) metric¶

In [36]:
# Creation of the RMSE metric:
n_folds = 5
kfold = KFold(n_folds, shuffle=True, random_state=42).get_n_splits(Xtrain)  
    
def rmse(y, y_pred):
    return np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y, y_pred))

def rmse_cv(model):
    rmse = np.sqrt(-cross_val_score(model, Xtrain, Ytrain, scoring="neg_mean_squared_error", cv=kfold, verbose= 0))
    return (rmse)

In [45]:
r_2_results = {'R-Squared':{},'Mean':{},'std':{}}   
rmse_results = {'RMSE':{},'Mean':{},'std':{}}

n_folds = 5
kfold = KFold(n_folds, shuffle=True, random_state=42).get_n_splits(Xtrain)

for name in base_models:
    model = base_models[name]
    r_2 = cross_val_score(model, Xtrain, Ytrain, scoring='r2', cv=kfold)   #R-Squared 
    rms = np.sqrt(-cross_val_score(model, Xtrain, Ytrain, cv=kfold,        #RMSE
                                   scoring='neg_mean_squared_error'))
    
    #save the R-Squared reults
    r_2_results['R-Squared'][name] = r_2
    r_2_results['Mean'][name] = r_2.mean()
    r_2_results['std'][name] = r_2.std()
    
    #save the RMSE reults
    rmse_results['RMSE'][name] = rms
    rmse_results['Mean'][name] = rms.mean()
    rmse_results['std'][name] = rms.std()

from plotly.offline import iplot

r_2_cv_results = pd.DataFrame(index=r_2_results['R-Squared'].keys())

#append the max R-Squared for each model to the dataframe
r_2_cv_results['Max'] = [r_2_results['R-Squared'][m].max() for m in r_2_results['R-Squared'].keys()]
#append the mean of all R-Squared for each model to the dataframe
r_2_cv_results['Mean'] = [r_2_results['Mean'][m] for m in r_2_results['Mean'].keys()]
#append the min R-Squared for each model to the dataframe
r_2_cv_results['Min'] = [r_2_results['R-Squared'][m].min() for m in r_2_results['R-Squared'].keys()]
#append the std of all R-Squared for each model to the dataframe

Great Live Area's the coeffient is 0.44, which means when Great Live Area increase 1 $ft^2$, the sale price can increse by exp(0.44) = $1.54 when other condition maintian same.

Conclusion¶

XGBoost and linear, Lasso, Ridge, ElasticNet regressons have decent $R^2$ and RMSE. They are much better than Random Forests, SVM and Desicion tree. Based on the XGBoost model, the TOP 10 features that influence the sale price are GrLivArea, BsmtFinType1, MSZoning_RL, MSZoning_RM, GarageFinish, Fireplaces, OverallQual, GarageCars, BsmtQual, GarageType_Attchd. For a seller, many of the features cannot be easily changed. There is one area that can add significant value to a home which is improve the overall quality.

furture improvement¶

There are some interaction between some features, like OveralConditon and Overal Quality, Kitchen condition and kitchen quality. I will add the interaction into the model to improve the model perfomance. Also, may add polynomial as well. Another way to improve the prediction is using stacking ensemble machine learning.
